Why Jerome Powell Must Go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as head of the US Federal Reserve – that is, to what may be the most powerful position within the world economy?
A wrong decision here can have serious consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to adequately regulate the banking system, thereby laying the groundwork for the worst global economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the political decision-makers' response to it had far-reaching political consequences; they exacerbated inequality and fostered a lasting feeling of dissatisfaction among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are a number of clichés as to why the current central bank chief, Jerome Powell, should be confirmed in office.
It would be a proof of non-partisanship.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
Someone with experience would be needed to lead us through the recovery following the pandemic.
And so on.
I heard exactly the same arguments 25 years ago when I was chairman of the economic advisory council of US President Bill Clinton and the confirmation of Greenspan in office was an issue.
They were sufficient to convince Clinton, and the country has paid dearly for his decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little attention to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and denied Volcker a second term in office after he had tamed inflation.
Reagan owed much to Volcker, but he favored deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, an adherent of Ayn Rand.
In economic policy, careful assessment and sensitivity to conflicting objectives are required.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that markets on their own are efficient, stable, fair, and characterized by competition?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the USA have always held clearly different but clearly articulated views on these issues (at least until the Republicans fell into populist delusions).
In my view, the Democrats are rightly concerned about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis has shown that unbridled markets are neither efficient nor stable.
Moreover, we know that traditionally, only in tight labor markets are marginalized groups integrated into the economy and wage disparities reduced.
The coming years are likely to be a test of strength for any U.S. Federal Reserve chairman.
The United States is already facing difficult decisions about what to do about inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially problems arising from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed view the unemployment rate of African Americans, who have still not regained their pre-pandemic level?
Would interest rate hikes (and the accompanying rise in unemployment) be worse as a remedy than the disease itself?
Equally important: While the incorrect pricing of mortgage-backed securities played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of an even stronger and more pervasive mispricing of assets related to climate change.
What should the Fed do in this regard?
Powell is not the man for the hour.
First, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump, thereby risking the financial health of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take action regarding climate risk, even though other central bankers worldwide have already declared this to be the central problem of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues are not part of the Fed's mandate, but he would be wrong.
It is part of the Fed's mandate to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater threat to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record suggests that he has never experienced a bad merger.
Such laxity is the last thing the economy needs right now.
A glaring lack of competition and insufficient regulation already enable excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses, and provide dominant players with more room to exploit others.
Some commentators credit Powell with the Fed's response to the pandemic.
But every second-year student would have known that during a recession, one must not tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT has argued, Powell is not particularly strongly committed to full employment.
On the contrary: Powell's record as a member of the US Federal Reserve Board, in terms of tightening monetary policy, was marked over the past decade by a series of misjudgments dating back to the "Taper Tantrum" of 2013.
Although many Fed observers insist that inequality is not the central bank's concern, it is a fact that the bank's policy has significant distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as an early increase in interest rates can choke off growth, a weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for stronger concentrations of market power.
And finally, the recent scandal involving stock transactions by senior Fed officials has undermined confidence in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparently lack of awareness of conflicts of interest, including in the management of some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has been a concern of mine for a long time.
After four years of Trump having already weakened trust in U.S. institutions, there is now a real risk that confidence in the integrity of the central bank will suffer further.
No Fed official should need an ethics officer to decide when certain stock transactions would appear improper.
The Fed resembles the U.S. Supreme Court in some respects.
This is supposed to be above politics, yet ever since Bush v. Gore we know that this is not the case.
Trump has made that clear to everyone who still had doubts.
The Fed is also supposed to be independent, yet Powell and Greenspan have clearly shown that this is not the case by following their party's deregulation agenda.
Yet while the central bank board makes important decisions that affect all aspects of the economy, power traditionally resides much more strongly in the hands of the central bank chairman than it does in the hands of the chief justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the central bank chairman who decides which issues come up for a vote and which topics are postponed or pushed forward.
The climate issue is just one example of how critically important it is who sits at the head of the table.
The USA needs a central bank that genuinely commits to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competition-driven financial sector.
Anyone who believes we can rely on unbridled markets or that regulation is already going too far lacks insight.
We need neither an ideologue like Greenspan nor a Wall Street-oriented lawyer like Powell.
What is needed is someone who possesses deep economic understanding and shares Biden's values and concerns regarding inflation and employment.
There are undoubtedly many people who meet these conditions.
But Biden does not have to look far to find someone who has already proven their abilities.
Lael Brainard is already on the central bank board, where she has demonstrated her competence and won the trust of the markets – without compromising her values.
Biden can have both: a central bank chair who ensures continuity and does not unsettle the markets, but who shares his economic and social program.
